[1] UK surveillance in wild birds, update
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Defra web-site, Wild birds, 20 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://www.defra.gov.uk/animalh/diseases/notifiable/disease/ai/wildbirds/survey-results.htm>

Examination of carcasses from unusually high mortality
events (die-offs) in wild birds (cumulative total figures since the
beginning of November 2005, updated 20 Apr 2006)
--------------------------------------------------
Number of enquiries received: 5436
Number of incidents with carcasses submitted: 3098
Number of incidents tested for avian influenza: 2898
Number of individual samples tested: 6161
Incidents positive for high pathogenicity avian influenza
virus (HPAI) subtypes H5 or H7: 1
Incidents positive for low pathogenicity avian influenza virus (LPAI)
subtypes H5 or H7: 0
Incidents positive for low pathogenicity avian influenza virus (LPAI)
subtypes other than H5 or H7: 0
Incidents negative for avian influenza virus: 2168
Incidents under test with some sample results to follow: 729
Note: An isolate of High Pathogenicity Avian Influenza (HPAI) virus
(subtype H5N1) was reported on 6 Mar 2006. The sample was taken from
a wild whooper swan found dead in the sea near Fife, Scotland. [The
information under the heading "Avian influenza (bird flu): Latest
situation", published elsewhere in the same web-site, reads: "High
pathogenic H5N1 avian influenza was confirmed on 6 Apr 2006 in a
partially decomposed swan found on the causeway in Cellardyke,
Scotland." - Mod.AS]
The total number of swans tested is 891.
Investigations in England and Wales are carried out by the Veterinary
Laboratories Agency (VLA), in Scotland by the Scottish Agricultural
Colleges Laboratories (SAC) and in Northern Ireland by DARD's
Veterinary Sciences Division laboratory.
Wild bird carcasses may not be received in all incidents in which
enquiries are received; this is because not all incidents fulfill the
requirements for the survey. For instance, further enquiries may
indicate that only one or 2 birds have died or that the mortality
level is not unusual.
Report compiled by the:
Surveillance, Zoonoses and Emerging Issues Division.
This page will be updated in the week commencing 24 Apr 2006.
--
