[2] Pakistan
Date: Thu, 20 Apr 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: Sapa AFP via Sunday Times, S.Africa, 20 Apr 2006 [edited]
<http://www.sundaytimes.co.za/zones/sundaytimesNEW/basket7st/basket7st1145526526.aspx>

Pakistani authorities have ordered the slaughter of 15 000 chickens
after a suspected 4th outbreak of the deadly bird flu virus, officials said.
Officials had quarantined a farm and several workers in Tarlai on the
outskirts of the capital Islamabad, said Mohammad Afzal, spokesman
for the Food, Agriculture and Livestock Ministry.
"We got a mortality report last night from a farm at Tarlai and
ordered the culling of 15 000 birds at the farm because of a
suspected outbreak of the H5N1 virus," Afzal said.
The area was sealed off with posters and placards saying "Restricted Area".
"There is very strong clinical evidence and symptoms of H5N1. We can
confirm the outbreak only after laboratory tests but protectively
we have culled all the birds at the farm," he said.
If confirmed, it would become the 2nd case near Islamabad and the 4th
in the country. Pakistan Sunday confirmed an H5N1 outbreak at another
chicken farm near Islamabad.
Its first bird flu cases were confirmed [in March 2006] at 2 chicken
farms in North West Frontier Province bordering Afghanistan.
[Map: <http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/pakistan.pdf>].
Authorities slaughtered 25 000 birds and sealed off the affected
farms in the northwestern market town of Charsadda and the hill
resort of Abbottabad.
No human cases have yet been reported despite a number of scare
stories in the local media and rising apprehension among Pakistanis.
"We are in touch with the health authorities and they have confirmed
to us that there is no human case reported to hospitals so far," Afzal said.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
